[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 12.3: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 12.3. It shows one way you could translate the ED-arrival-forecasting pipeline into working Python using boto3 against Amazon Kinesis Data Streams (here represented by an in-memory `MockStream` of synthetic ADT records), Amazon S3 (here represented by an in-process `MockS3` writer), AWS Glue (here represented by pure-Python aggregation in `aggregate_arrivals_to_hourly`), Amazon SageMaker (here represented by pure-Python `PoissonVolumeModel` and `AcuityMixModel` classes that stand in for negative-binomial regression and a multinomial classifier), AWS Step Functions (here represented by sequential function calls), Amazon DynamoDB (mocked with `MockTable`), Amazon EventBridge (mocked with `MockEventBus`), and Amazon CloudWatch (mocked with `MockCloudWatch`). The demo generates two years of synthetic ADT registration records with realistic hour-of-day, day-of-week, and weather-driven arrival patterns plus an ESI mix that shifts across the day, so you can see the hourly aggregation, the feature engineering, the volume model, the acuity classifier, the prediction-interval calculation, and the DynamoDB load work end-to-end without provisioning anything. It is not production-ready. There is no real Kinesis stream, no real Glue ETL, no real SageMaker training job, no real Step Functions state machine, no real DynamoDB table, no real EventBridge bus, no real CloudWatch alarms, no late-record reconciliation, no diversion-window handling, no per-Lambda IAM least privilege, no KMS customer-managed keys, no VPC endpoints, no surge-plan trigger logic, and no inpatient-census coupling. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of an ED arrival forecasting pipeline that respects the hourly-cadence discipline, the volume-and-acuity-as-separate-models discipline, the prediction-interval-not-point-estimate discipline, and the audit-everything discipline this recipe demands. It is not something you would point at a real ED on Monday morning. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The code maps to the five pseudocode steps from the main recipe: aggregate the raw ADT registration stream into hourly counts per ED per ESI level (Step 1); join in calendar, weather, surveillance, lag, and event features to build the modeling-ready table (Step 2); train a count regression for total hourly volume and a multinomial classifier for the per-acuity share with held-out evaluation (Step 3); generate forecasts at 4-hour, 12-hour, and 24-hour horizons with prediction intervals and an ESI breakdown (Step 4); load the forecast records to DynamoDB keyed by `ed_id` with a `forecast_for_hour#generated_at` sort key plus a `CURRENT` pointer per future hour (Step 5). The synthetic ADT records, ED identifiers, weather observations, flu indices, event flags, and ESI assignments in the demo are fictional; nothing in this file should be interpreted as real ED registration data from any real institution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You will need the AWS SDK for Python:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demo runs against the Python standard library plus boto3; no other packages are imported. Production deployments swap the demo's pure-Python `PoissonVolumeModel` for a real count regression library (statsmodels' `GLM` with the negative-binomial family, Prophet with regressors and a Poisson likelihood, or the SageMaker DeepAR built-in algorithm for multi-ED neural forecasting), and swap the demo's `AcuityMixModel` for a real multinomial classifier (scikit-learn's `LogisticRegression` with `multi_class='multinomial'` plus calibrated probabilities, or a gradient-boosted multinomial classifier like LightGBM); the Gap to Production section spells out the substitutions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In production you would also configure an Amazon Kinesis Data Stream (or Amazon HealthLake) for the raw ADT registration ingest, an Amazon S3 bucket for the hourly aggregated arrivals zone, the weather and surveillance feeds zone, the model-artifact zone, and the forecast-output zone, an AWS Glue Streaming job (or EMR Serverless with Spark Structured Streaming) that consumes the ADT stream and writes hourly counts per ED per ESI level back to S3 partitioned by `(ed_id, date)`, an Amazon SageMaker training image with statsmodels, scikit-learn, and a calibrated-probability library installed (a custom container built on the SageMaker scikit-learn base or the SageMaker DeepAR built-in algorithm for the multi-ED neural option), an AWS Step Functions state machine that orchestrates the hourly inference cycle (latest-hour aggregation -> feature refresh -> volume + acuity inference -> forecast composition -> DynamoDB load) and the weekly retraining cycle (full feature build -> volume training -> acuity training -> quality gate -> atomic endpoint deploy), an Amazon DynamoDB table for the served forecasts keyed by `ed_id` with a sort key combining `forecast_for_hour` and `generated_at` plus a `CURRENT#<forecast_for_hour>` pointer per ED per future hour, an Amazon EventBridge schedule that fires the hourly inference state machine on the top of every hour and the weekly retraining state machine on a Sunday-night cadence, AWS Lambda functions for the lightweight transforms (weather API pull, flu surveillance refresh, forecast post-processing, DynamoDB loader, optional Bedrock-based explanation generation), Amazon CloudWatch dashboards and alarms for pipeline failures and per-horizon forecast drift, and a thin integration layer (typically a JSON API or a DynamoDB-backed dashboard query) that surfaces the forecasts to the charge-nurse dashboard, the staffing scheduler, and the surge-plan trigger logic. The demo replaces all of these with a single in-process Python file so the focus stays on the hourly aggregation, the feature engineering, the volume + acuity modeling, the prediction-interval math, and the forecast composition rather than on the platform plumbing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kinesis:GetRecords`, `kinesis:GetShardIterator`, and `kinesis:DescribeStream` on the ADT ingest stream (or the equivalent HealthLake `DescribeFHIRDatastore` and `SearchWithGet` permissions when ingesting full FHIR rather than raw HL7 ADT)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject` and `s3:PutObject` on the hourly arrivals prefix, the weather and surveillance prefixes, the model-artifact prefix, and the forecast-output prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `glue:StartJobRun`, `glue:GetJobRun`, and the Glue service role's permissions for the streaming aggregation job
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:DescribeTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `sagemaker:UpdateEndpointWeightsAndCapacities` on the volume + acuity endpoint
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:BatchWriteItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `dynamodb:GetItem` on the `ed-forecasts` table, scoped to the specific table ARN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `events:PutEvents` on the ed-forecast-events bus for emitting pipeline-lifecycle events (run started, latest hour aggregated, forecast generated, forecast loaded, drift alarm raised)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `states:StartExecution` on the ed-forecast Step Functions state machines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData` for the operational metrics (per-horizon MAPE, per-horizon coverage of the prediction interval, acuity-classifier macro F1, ingest-to-forecast latency, late-record reconciliation rate)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the customer-managed keys protecting the Kinesis stream, the S3 prefixes, the DynamoDB table, and the model-artifact bucket
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `secretsmanager:GetSecretValue` on any weather-API or surveillance-feed credentials secrets pinned to the current rotation version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Scope each Lambda's IAM role to the specific resource ARNs it touches. The tutorial-level permissions above are fine for learning and will fail any serious IAM review. The aggregation Lambda has read access to the Kinesis stream and write access to the hourly-arrivals S3 prefix, but no SageMaker or DynamoDB permissions. The inference orchestrator has SageMaker InvokeEndpoint permissions and DynamoDB write access on the forecasts table, but no Kinesis read access. Avoid wildcard actions and resources in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things worth knowing upfront:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **ADT records are PHI by definition.** An HL7 v2 ADT-A04 (registration) message carries the patient's name, MRN, date of birth, address, chief complaint, and triage notes. Even after you bucket the records into hourly arrival counts, the lineage back to identifiable patients still exists. The Kinesis stream, the S3 prefix, the DynamoDB table, and the forecast outputs all live under a HIPAA-eligible architecture with SSE-KMS encryption, VPC endpoints, and CloudTrail audit. The demo redacts patient identifiers immediately at the boundary; production never carries them past the aggregation step in the first place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Hours are local-time hours, not UTC.** ED operations are local. A morning shift change at 07:00 happens at 07:00 local time, regardless of what UTC offset that is. Bucketing arrivals by UTC hour and then displaying them in local time produces subtle off-by-one errors on daylight-saving-transition days that confuse charge nurses for years afterward. The demo bucket function takes the ED's local timezone explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The acuity model is sample-efficient, not flashy.** ESI 1 (resuscitation) arrivals are rare. A multinomial classifier trained on historical ESI assignments learns the calendar-and-weather correlates of acuity-mix shifts more reliably than a separate volume forecast per ESI level. The demo follows the volume-plus-acuity-share approach for that reason.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The prediction interval is the operational primitive, not the point estimate.** Charge nurses staff to absorb the surge, not the average. The 80th and 95th percentiles of the forecast distribution drive call-in decisions; the mean is interesting but secondary. The demo emits both `volume_lower_80` / `volume_upper_80` and `volume_lower_95` / `volume_upper_95` because the dashboard cares about both.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB rejects Python `float`.** Every count, percentile bound, lead-hour, ESI share, and confidence threshold passes through `Decimal` on its way in and on its way out. The `_to_decimal` helper handles it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The example collapses many Lambdas, Glue jobs, and SageMaker calls into a single Python file.** In production the Kinesis-to-S3 aggregation Glue job, the feature-build Glue job, the SageMaker inference call, the forecast-composition Lambda, and the DynamoDB-loader Lambda are separate units of work with their own IAM roles, error handling, retries, and DLQs. Comments call out where the boundaries should fall.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
